  <h1>Hunt of a Lifetime</h1>
  <p>Providing once-in-a-lifetime hunting opportunities for terminally ill youth.</p>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="content-block">
    <h2>About the Program</h2>
    <p>G.R.A.Y. is a recognized sponsor for the Oregon Department of Fish and Wildlife's Hunt of a Lifetime program. Children diagnosed with a terminal illness have little ability to wait to draw big game hunting tags through the regular process. This program provides them with an extraordinary opportunity to experience hunting in Oregon.</p>

    <h2>Background</h2>
    <p>Senate Bill 694 in Oregon authorized free tags for qualifying youth. The program enables children and young adults with terminal illnesses to obtain deer, elk, or antelope tags without entering competitive drawings, giving them a once-in-a-lifetime outdoor experience.</p>

    <h2>Program Details</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Qualifying organizations must be approved by ODFW</li>
      <li>Participants must have a terminal illness and be between ages 12 and 21</li>
      <li>Available tags: 10 deer, 10 elk, and 5 antelope statewide</li>
      <li>Organizations are limited to a maximum of 5 tags</li>
      <li>One tag per child</li>
      <li>Deer and elk hunting seasons run September 1 through November 30</li>
      <li>Antelope hunting season runs September 1 through September 30</li>
      <li>Hunter safety certification and licensing requirements apply</li>
      <li>Both Oregon residents and non-residents are eligible</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>A Meaningful Opportunity</h2>
    <p>This program provides a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity for children diagnosed with a terminal illness to experience the outdoors and pursue big game hunting in Oregon without the barriers of the competitive tag drawing system.</p>
  </div>
</section>

